    title: "Saturdays at the Corner Bakery",
    text: "When I turned sixteen, my parents decided it was time I learned what they called \"the value of a pound\". My mother spotted a card in the window of Hartley's, the small bakery at the end of our street, advertising for a Saturday assistant. I had walked past that window a thousand times, breathing in the smell of warm bread, but I had never imagined standing on the other side of the counter. To be honest, my first reaction was reluctance. Saturdays were for lying in bed until midday and meeting friends in the park, not for getting up at half past six. Still, the promise of my own money was hard to resist, and after a short, friendly interview with Mrs Hartley herself, I was told to report for duty the following weekend. My first morning was, frankly, a disaster. I dropped a tray of croissants, gave a customer change for a twenty-pound note when she had paid with a ten, and managed to label the gluten-free loaves as ordinary ones, which Mrs Hartley said could have had serious consequences for anyone with an allergy. I fully expected to be told not to come back. Instead, she poured me a cup of tea during the mid-morning quiet spell and said something I have never forgotten: \"Nobody is born knowing how to do a job. You're only useless if you make the same mistake twice.\" That single sentence changed my attitude completely. Over the following weeks I learned to arrive ten minutes early, to double-check every price, and to greet the regular customers by name. There was Mr Okafor, who bought two seeded rolls every Saturday and always asked about my schoolwork, and an elderly couple who shared one slice of carrot cake with two forks because, as they cheerfully admitted, their doctor had told them to cut down on sugar. What surprised me most was how much I came to enjoy the rhythm of the work. There was real satisfaction in seeing the shelves, empty and clean at seven in the morning, gradually fill with loaves and pastries, and then empty again by mid-afternoon as the neighbourhood carried our work home in paper bags. My friends teased me about smelling of flour, and I did miss a few birthday gatherings, but I noticed changes in myself that made the sacrifice feel worthwhile. I was more patient, better at mental arithmetic, and far more confident talking to adults. When exam season arrived and I had to give the job up temporarily, Mrs Hartley handed me an envelope with a small bonus inside. \"That's not for the hours,\" she said. \"It's for the improvement.\" Looking back now, I realise the wages were almost the least important thing I took from Hartley's. The money disappeared long ago on trainers and cinema tickets, yet the habits I formed behind that counter - punctuality, care, and the courage to admit an error - have stayed with me through every job since. My parents wanted me to learn the value of a pound. What I actually learned was the value of being trusted with responsibility, which, as far as I can tell, no wage can really measure.",
