    id: "f-rmc1-03",
    title: "The Wrong Turn in the Valley",
    text: "It was my father's idea, of course. Ever since he had watched a documentary about a family who cycled across Europe, he had been dropping hints about \"a proper adventure\", and by the spring he had worn the rest of us down. The plan sounded reasonable enough on paper: five days following a well-marked cycle route through a river valley, staying each night in small guesthouses he had booked months in advance. My mother, my younger sister Ellie and I were promised gentle slopes, charming villages and, in Dad's confident phrase, \"absolutely nothing that can go wrong\". The first two days, to be fair, were close to perfect. The path ran flat beside the water, the weather was kind, and even Ellie, who had complained loudly about giving up a week of her holidays, stopped grumbling once she discovered that every village seemed to sell excellent ice cream. The trouble began on the third morning, at a junction where a fallen sign lay face-down in the grass. Dad, who regarded asking for directions as a form of personal defeat, studied his map for about ten seconds and announced that we should take the left-hand track. My mother suggested, mildly, that we might check with the walkers we could see further down the right-hand path. Dad had already set off. For the first hour the track climbed gently, then less gently, and by midday we were pushing our bikes up a stony path while the river, which we were supposed to be following, glittered far below us on the other side of the valley. Ellie's mood, predictably, collapsed along with her energy, and my mother's silence became the loud kind that every family recognises. When the path finally ended at a locked forestry gate, even Dad had to admit that the situation was, as he put it, \"not entirely ideal\". What happened next was the part none of us predicted. As we stood arguing about whether to retrace our route, an elderly farmer appeared on a quad bike, followed by an extremely muddy dog. Between his limited English and my mother's phrasebook German, we learned that a landslide had closed the main cycle path that morning, and that everyone who had taken the \"correct\" route was now stuck behind it, waiting for buses. Our wrong turn, in other words, was the only way through. The farmer led us along a farm track, insisted on refilling our water bottles at his house, and sent us off with a bag of apples and directions so precise that even Dad could not misinterpret them. We rolled into our guesthouse three hours late, filthy and exhausted, to find the owner astonished to see us at all; the other guests had cancelled. Over dinner, Dad attempted to claim that he had suspected something was wrong with the main route all along, at which point the whole table, including the guesthouse owner, burst out laughing. The rest of the holiday passed without drama, but it is that third day we still talk about, years later. Ellie maintains it proves Dad should never be allowed to navigate again. Dad insists it proves the value of instinct over signposts. My mother just says that if the trip taught us anything, it is that the stories worth retelling are never the ones that go according to plan.",
