    id: "f-rmc1-04",
    title: "Never Too Late for the Cello",
    text: "At the age of forty-three, Daniel Mercer walked into a music shop, pointed at a second-hand cello, and did something he had been quietly planning for twenty-five years. As a teenager he had begged his parents for lessons, but money was short and the school's only cello was permanently on loan to a girl two years above him. Life then did what life does: college, work, marriage, children. The wish never disappeared; it simply waited. \"I kept telling myself I'd start when things calmed down,\" he says. \"Eventually I realised things never calm down. You just have to begin.\" The trigger, in the end, was unexpectedly small. Watching his ten-year-old daughter struggle through her first term of violin practice, Daniel heard himself repeating the encouraging phrases all parents use - mistakes are how you learn, nobody starts out good - and realised he did not apply a word of it to himself. That evening he searched online for adult beginners' cello lessons, half hoping there would be none nearby. There were three teachers within cycling distance. His first lessons were humbling in ways he had not anticipated. It was not the sore fingers or the aching shoulder, though there was plenty of both. It was the strangeness of being a complete beginner again in middle age. In his job as a project manager he was the person with answers; on Tuesday evenings he was a man producing sounds that, in his teacher's tactful words, \"had character\". Progress that a child might make in a month took him a whole term. Research on learning suggests adults are actually quite efficient students - they understand structure, they practise with purpose, and they know why they are there - but they carry one heavy disadvantage: embarrassment. Children will happily play a wrong note in front of anyone. Adults, Daniel discovered, would rather practise in a locked room with the windows shut. His teacher, a patient woman named Iveta, attacked this problem directly. She ran a termly \"catastrophe concert\" for her adult students, an informal evening where mistakes were not merely tolerated but celebrated, with a small prize for whoever recovered from an error most gracefully. \"The first time, I nearly cancelled with a fake illness,\" Daniel admits. \"By the third one, I was disappointed if I didn't have a disaster to laugh about.\" Two years on, Daniel plays in an amateur string group that meets in a community hall on Sunday afternoons. He is, he cheerfully insists, the weakest player there, and he no longer cares. What he has gained, he says, goes well beyond music. His concentration has improved, work stress loosens its grip the moment he opens the case, and he and his daughter now moan companionably about scales over dinner. She recently pointed out that he practises more than she does, which he regards as the finest compliment of his adult life. His advice for anyone hesitating over a childhood dream is simple. \"People wait for permission - the right age, the right time, enough talent. That permission never arrives, because nobody but you can issue it. I spent twenty-five years being someone who wished he played the cello. Now I'm just someone who plays it badly. I promise you, the second one feels infinitely better.\"",
