    id: "f-rmc1-05",
    title: "The Night the Regal Lit Up Again",
    text: "For thirty-one years, the Regal cinema stood dark on the main square of Alderbridge, a small market town of six thousand people. Older residents remembered queuing there for tickets in its heyday; younger ones knew it only as the boarded-up building pigeons argued over. Various schemes had come and gone - a supermarket chain lost interest, a plan for flats collapsed - and most people assumed the Regal would eventually be demolished. That it is now open again, showing films five nights a week to healthy audiences, is largely down to a retired postman, a sixteen-year-old film fanatic, and several hundred people who refused to accept that their town was too small to matter. The story began, improbably, at a bus stop. Ken Duffy, who had delivered letters in Alderbridge for four decades, overheard a teenager named Sofia Marsh complaining to a friend that seeing any film meant an expensive forty-minute bus ride to the multiplex in the city, and that half the time the last bus home left before the film ended. Ken, who had taken his own children to the Regal in the 1980s, mentioned that the town used to have a cinema of its own. \"She looked at me as if I'd said we used to have a castle,\" he recalls. \"That's when I thought: why not again?\" What followed was three years of patient, unglamorous effort. Ken and Sofia - who quickly became the campaign's most persuasive public speaker, despite being too young to sign any of its legal documents - organised open meetings, film quizzes and outdoor screenings on the recreation ground to prove there was an appetite. The breakthrough came when the town council, impressed by a petition carrying more signatures than the town had households, agreed to buy the building and lease it to a community group for a token rent. The renovation money was raised through community shares: local people invested sums from twenty-five pounds upwards, becoming part-owners with a vote at annual meetings. Builders discovered the original 1930s ceiling decorations intact above a false ceiling, and a retired electrician spent an entire winter restoring the foyer lights for nothing more than tea and biscuits. Not every decision was straightforward. Some investors wanted the latest blockbusters every night, arguing this was the only way to compete; others wanted classic films and documentaries. The compromise - mainstream titles at weekends, alternative programming midweek, and a monthly matinee for parents with babies - has proved shrewder than anyone expected, drawing different audiences who might otherwise never mix. On reopening night, the queue stretched around the square, and Ken cut the ribbon with Sofia, now studying film at college and back for the occasion. The Regal will never make anyone rich. Any surplus goes into a fund for equipment and cheap tickets for schools. But its value, argue its volunteers, cannot be counted at the box office. The café in the foyer has become somewhere teenagers and pensioners actually talk to each other; local shops report busier Friday evenings; and the town has acquired something harder to measure - the confidence that comes from having rescued a piece of itself. As Sofia put it in her speech that first night: \"They kept telling us Alderbridge was too small for a cinema. It turns out no town is too small for a good idea.\"",
